  "text": "Indirect ELISA was performed to test T. gondii infection in dogs as described by elsewhere [CITATION_1] . Briefly, microplates were coated with TLA, GRA1, or GRA7, respectively. After washing, 100 μl of canine serum diluted 1:50 was added to each well, and incubated for 3 h at 37°C, then 100 μl of horseradish peroxidase-conjugated sheep anti-dog IgG antibodies (Abcam, USA) diluted 1:20,000 was added. After incubation for 1 h at room temperature and washing, color was developed by the addition of a substrate solution containing tetramethylbenzidine chromogenic substrate TMB (Thermo Fisher Scientific, USA), and stopped by 2 M H 2 SO 4 . The optical densities (ODs) were measured at 450 nm in a microplate reader (BioTek, USA). ELISA results were determined for each serum in duplicate. The cut-off point of OD values of a positive samples was set to be at least two times higher than that of the negative samples at any dilution point.",
